    <h1>Ni&#xAD;co&#xAD;lette Yip (left), 28, fash&#xAD;ion de&#xAD;signer, fash&#xAD;ion la&#xAD;bel The Sal&#xAD;vages</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201031/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-31"><time>2020-10-31</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE DESIGN</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>I like nat­u­ral fab­rics but sus­tain­able or re­pur­posed ma­te­ri­als in­trigue me too.</p>
    <p>My work chair is a pre-owned Sam­sonite Chicory Cabin Chair (right), an un­der­rated mid-cen­tury mod­ern de­sign that is of­ten over­looked.</p>
    <p>I use this chair be­cause it’s sim­ple and hon­est in its use of ma­te­ri­als. It is also quite sturdy and does the job as well as any nor­mal of­fice chairs.</p>
    <p>It is un­com­pli­cated and un­em­bel­lished, and be­cause it is a pre-owned piece, it makes me like it even more.</p>
    <p>To me, a chair is a piece of fur­ni­ture that in­ter­acts closely with the body, so er­gonomics should not be com­pro­mised in favour of aes­thet­ics.</p>
    <p>Sim­ple de­signs that are also beau­ti­ful are usu­ally the hard­est to de­sign, even more so when prac­ti­cal­ity is con­sid­ered.</p>

